      <div class="content-container l-container clearfix"> 
       <div class="content-column"> 
        <div id="main" tabindex="-1" role="main" class="main"> 
         <div class="m m-key-messages m-hero m-hero-accent pdf-show"> 
          <div class="m-h"> 
           <h3>Summary</h3> 
          </div> 
          <div class="m-b"> 
           <ul>
            <li>A kilojoule (or Calorie) is a unit of energy.</li>
            <li>The kilojoule content of foods depends on the amount of carbohydrates, fats and proteins present in the food. If we regularly eat more kilojoules than our body needs, the excess will be stored as body fat.</li>
           </ul> 
          </div> 
         </div> 
         <div id="phbody_1_phcontentbody_2_pnl" class="l-content fn_longpage">
           We eat food to fuel our bodies for energy, growth and repair. Carbohydrates, proteins and fats are broken down by the digestive system into their simplest components, being simple sugars, amino acids and fatty acids. 
          <br>
          <br>Carbohydrates are the bodys preferred fuel, although proteins and fats can also be converted into energy. Food energy is measured in kilojoules (kJ). The common term for this used to be calorie, but kilojoule is the term now accepted internationally. This unit of measurement allows us to talk about how much energy a food contains and how much energy is burned up during exercise.
          <br>
          <br>
          <h2>Energy as kilojoules</h2>
          <br>A kilojoule is a unit of measure of energy, in the same way that kilometres measure distance. Food energy can also be measured in terms of the nutritional or large Calorie (Cal), which has the same energy value as 4.186 kilojoules (kJ). This should not be confused with the small or gram calorie, which is used by scientists to measure the amount of energy required to heat water. There are 1,000 (small) calories in one (large) Calorie, which is why it is also sometimes known as a kilocalorie. 
          <br>
          <br>4.184 kilojoules = 4,184 joules = 1 Calorie = 1 kilocalorie = 1,000 calories
          <br>
          <br>
          <h2>Kilojoules in food</h2>
          <br>The foods we eat provide energy, which is measured in kilojoules. Just how much energy depends on the amount of carbohydrate, protein and fat the food contains. Foods such as fruits, vegetables and legumes are relatively low energy (kilojoule) dense foods.
          <br>
          <br>Foods which are high in fats, added sugars or alcohol are by far the most energy-dense foods. This is why they should only be consumed in moderation, particularly if you are overweight or obese. 
          <br>
          <br>The energy value 
          <b>per gram</b> of various food components includes:
          <ul>
           <li><b>fat</b>  37 kJ (9 Cal)  not all fatty acids may provide the same amount of energy</li>
           <li><b>alcohol</b>  29 kJ (7 Cal)</li>
           <li><b>carbohydrates</b>  16 kJ (4 Cal)  not all carbohydrates may provide the same amount of energy</li>
           <li><b>protein</b>  17 kJ (4 Cal)</li>
           <li><b>dietary fibre</b>  13 kJ (3 Cal)  if fermented by bacteria in the large intestine</li>
           <li><b>water</b>  0 kJ (0 Cal).</li>
          </ul>
          <h2>Research into energy values of food</h2>
          <br>Research into fat and carbohydrate metabolism is changing our understanding about the energy values of different types of fats and carbohydrates. Research indicates that how the body metabolises (breaks down) different foods may be important. It appears that not all fats or carbohydrates have the same energy value as their chemical analysis in the test tube might indicate. 
          <br>
          <br>
          <h2>Some fats are broken down faster</h2>
          <br>Animal studies show that polyunsaturated, monounsaturated and saturated fatty acids are broken down differently in the body and may not be used in the same way. Some fats, like polyunsaturated fats (especially omega-3 fatty acids from fish oils), may be more easily used up from fat stores during exercise than fats from other animal sources. 
          <br>
          <br>This suggests that saturated fat may be more likely to go into and stay in fat cells than some forms of polyunsaturated fat and possibly monounsaturated fat. 
          <br>
          <br>
          <h2>Sugars and carbohydrates</h2>
          <br>Carbohydrates are broken down by the body into sugars or glucose. Some carbohydrate foods, such as white bread, processed cereals and biscuits are metabolised faster than others and are known as foods with a high glycaemic index (GI). Some research suggests that a diet dominated by carbohydrate foods with a high GI is associated with greater body fatness. However, both high GI and low GI foods can be included in a healthy diet.
          <br>
          <br>Understanding the GI of different foods is particularly important for people with diabetes, as low GI foods provide a slower, more sustained release of glucose into the bloodstream, helping to keep blood glucose levels stable.
          <br>
          <br>
          <h2>Our energy requirements vary</h2>
          <br>Energy requirements differ from one person to the next because of genetic predisposition, build, gender, age, metabolism, environment and amount of regular physical activity.
          <br>
          <br>A persons energy requirements can also differ from one day to the next, and as we grow older. For example:
          <ul>
           <li>Young children and adolescents require high amounts of energy to fuel their growth and development.</li>
           <li>Women need more energy during certain stages of their reproductive lives, such as pregnancy and breastfeeding. It is thought that daily energy needs increase on average by about 1,800 kJ for pregnant women in the second and third trimesters, and around 2,000 kJ during breastfeeding.</li>
           <li>Muscle tissue has a big appetite for kilojoules. The more muscle mass you have, the more kilojoules you will burn.</li>
           <li>Men generally have higher energy requirements than women, because they have more muscle tissue. </li>
           <li>As we age, activity levels are often reduced, which causes a loss of muscle tissue, and so our energy requirements tend to decrease. Various other age-related changes to the metabolism also contribute to reduced energy requirements. Its not clear how much of the muscle lost during ageing is a result of the ageing process or due to reduced activity. Strength and resistance training in older adults (even the very old and frail) seems to help reduce or prevent the decline in muscle mass that is generally observed with ageing.</li>
          </ul>
          <h2>Eating too many kilojoules</h2>
          <br>When we regularly eat more energy than our body needs, the excess is stored inside fat cells. Just one kg of body fat contains the equivalent of 37,000 kJ. To lose one kg of body fat in a month, you would need to reduce consumption by around 1200 kJ a day. 
          <br>
          <br>
          <h2>How to lose excess weight</h2>
          <br>The best way to lose excess weight is to enjoy a variety of foods from each of the five food groups in the amounts recommended and, importantly, to exercise regularly. 
          <br>
          <br>Exercise not only uses up stored energy, but also helps to stimulate muscle development. Remember, the more muscle tissue you have, the more kilojoules you can burn. 
          <br>
          <br>If you are over 40, have a pre-existing medical condition or you havent exercised for some time, see your doctor before starting a new fitness program.
          <br>
          <br>
          <h2>Where to get help</h2>
          <ul>
           <li>Your doctor</li>
           <li>Dietitians Association of Australia Tel. 1800 812 942</li>
           <li>Nutrition Australia Tel. (03) 8341 5800</li>
          </ul>
          <h2>Things to remember</h2>
          <ul>
           <li>A kilojoule (or Calorie) is a unit of energy.</li>
           <li>The kilojoule content of foods depends on the amount of carbohydrates, fats and proteins present in the food. If we regularly eat more kilojoules than our body needs, the excess will be stored as body fat.</li>
          </ul> 
         </div>

          <div class="mc-cols fn_equalHeights mc-multi" data-heights-type="mc-cols-multi">

             <div class="m-h"> 
              <h3 class="ctn-main-heading"> <span class="cta-heading-text">Weight management</span> </h3> 
             </div>

        <div id="complementary" role="complementary" class="complementary"> 
         <div class="m m-gallery-list is-loading is-gallery"> 
          <ol class="gallery-items"> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/cut_down_on_salt_first-tile_1050x590.png?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=4F68E1159A8DDB59826C9999C3AB51E72CD73839"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/cut_down_on_salt_first-tile_1050x590.png" alt="Cut down on salt intro tile"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <p>Many of us are consuming around eight or nine times more salt (sodium) than we should largely because its hidden in many of the foods we eat. A whopping two thirds of salt comes from processed foods. Too much salt can lead to high blood pressure, which puts us at risk of stroke, heart disease and chronic kidney disease. Try these simple tips and cut down your intake.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/takeaways_1050x590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=D545F1F4E557167C19027AD66E40EC057A8FD691"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/takeaways_1050x590.jpg" alt="Picking up donut to eat"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Limit bought food</h3> 
              <p>Food eaten at restaurants, cafes and from takeaway outlets can be much higher in salt than food prepared at home. The best bet is to <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/food-to-have-sometimes" target="_new">make them occasional treats</a> rather than part of your regular diet. Theyre also high in <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/kilojoules-and-calories" target="_new">kilojoules</a>, <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/fats-and-oils" target="_new">saturated fat</a> and <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/sugar" target="_new">sugars</a>. And if you think that sweets are immune from high levels of salt, think again  muffins, donuts and pancakes with maple syrup contain more than 400 mg, which is above safe levels. Dont be fooled by healthier options either  a Caesar salad bought over the counter may contain more salt than the average cheeseburger! </p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/readlabels_1050x590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=DAABFDF0B56BFBFB2C7B25450AC6182869DEC9E1"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/readlabels_1050x590.jpg" alt="Woman reading labels on canned food"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title"><a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/food-labels" target="_new">Read food labels</a></h3> 
              <p>The amount of salt in foods can vary considerably between brands. Look for products with 'no-added salt', or at least 'reduced' or 'low salt'. <b>The best choices are those with less than 120 mg of sodium per 100 g</b>. If you have kids, watch how much theyre consuming  too much salt in childhood can lead to a lifetime of health risks. If you need help choosing foods, <a href="http://healthstarrating.gov.au/internet/healthstarrating/publishing.nsf/content/home" target="_new">check out the governments Health Star Rating</a>  the more stars a product has the healthier it is. <br> <br> Hint: when using canned vegetables, choose ones with 'no-added salt'.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/ditchshaker_1050-x-590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=75EB61F573615F222D268B17917C86FCD4C8BDF0"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/ditchshaker_1050-x-590.jpg" alt="Ditch the salt shaker"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Ditch the salt shaker</h3> 
              <p>Try to break the habit of automatically salting your meals at the table. And when cooking, dont add salt. A better option is to add <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/herbs" target="_new">herbs</a>, a splash of <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/olive-oil" target="_new">olive oil</a>, citrus juice or zest to enhance flavours. Spices such as pepper or cumin are great alternatives too. <br> <br> Hint: grow some <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/ingredientsprofiles/Thyme" target="_new">thyme</a> in a pot it adds flavour to soups, stews, and meat. </p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/clever_kitchen_1050-x-590.png?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=44BC86DF0BA323C538990E3D31C53EF0F4BBAAA1"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/clever_kitchen_1050-x-590.png" alt="Variety of fresh herbs"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Get clever in the kitchen</h3> 
              <p>Dont add salt to food when cooking. Instead, give your meals a boost with <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/herbs" target="_new">herbs</a> (e.g. <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/ingredientsprofiles/Basil" target="_new">basil</a>, <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/ingredientsprofiles/Coriander" target="_new">coriander</a>), spices (e.g. cumin, pepper), fresh ginger, <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/ingredientsprofiles/Garlic" target="_new">garlic</a>, <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/ingredientsprofiles/Chillies" target="_new">chilli</a>, vinegar and <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/ingredientsprofiles/Lemon" target="_new">lemon</a> juice or zest. If it's hard to cut out salt altogether, do it slowly and introduce new flavours gradually. Seasonings are high in salt too  use low or reduced-salt stocks, stock powder and gravy powder and dilute them more than the instructions recommend. When cooking pasta, noodles, rice or vegetables dont add salt to water. <br> <br> Hint: dont add the amount of salt stated in recipes  try adding half or less. If a recipe includes other salty ingredients like stock powder, Asian sauces, olives, capers, anchovies, bacon, ham or smoked salmon, then you shouldnt need extra salt. </p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/taste_it_1050-x-590.png?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=1709B39A68849833439150C65303185D8D1D926A"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/taste_it_1050-x-590.png" alt="Woman tasting soup"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Think you can taste it?</h3> 
              <p>As consumers, we put a lot of trust in businesses who make our food. But when it comes salt, <a href="http://www.donttrustyourtastebuds.com.au/" target="_new">can you trust your tastebuds?</a> Foods dont have to taste salty to be high in salt. Take control and get into the habit of reading labels.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/convenience_no_1050x590.png?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=33F4D4DCE7093306863840C5E8BDF65142CDA40C"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/convenience_no_1050x590.png" alt="Instant noodles in cup"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Convenience a no go</h3> 
              <p>In this busy world, a lot of us are looking for ways to spend less time in the kitchen and thats why convenience products and packaged foods are so popular. Most of these foods are high in salt and best avoided. Cut back on things like  deli meats, flavoured instant pasta, instant noodles, savoury snack foods and crackers, instant cup-a-soups, dehydrated soup mixes and 'heat and eat' frozen or refrigerated meals. Use the <a href="http://healthstarrating.gov.au/internet/healthstarrating/publishing.nsf/content/home" target="_new">governments Health Star Rating</a> to choose lower sodium products. Even better, cut down the amount of these products youre consuming and go fresh  it really is best! </p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/allsaltisthesame_1050x590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=007F2DAAC8F57B946EAC95AB8D3BBE2F69691A8A"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/allsaltisthesame_1050x590.jpg" alt="Different types of salt"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">All salt is the same</h3> 
              <p>Don't be fooled by trendy claims  all <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/salt" target="_new">salt</a> is the same. Whether it's pink, rock or vegetable, it's still salt, and has the same effect on our health. Any salt contains sodium, and is just the same as ordinary table salt.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/measuring_cups_1050x590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=7BC13744CF00E833E59027921FE6859A6934865D"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/measuring_cups_1050x590.jpg" alt="Measuring cups"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">How much is too much?</h3> 
              <p>We need sodium to regulate fluids in our body  most of us can get it naturally in our diet without it being added. We only need a small amount each day but many of us are eating way more. <b>Adults should eat less than 2300 mg (or 5 g) of sodium  about a teaspoon of salt a day</b>. <b>Children need less than one quarter of a teaspoon of salt per day</b>. The adequate intake of sodium for children starts at around 0.5 g salt (1-3 year olds) to 1 g salt (913 year olds). <br> <br> Hint: got <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/conditionsandtreatments/blood-pressure-high-hypertension" target="_new">high blood pressure</a>  reduce your salt intake to 1600 mg (4 g) per day. And dont forget to <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/talking-with-your-doctor" target="_new">talk with your doctor or health practitioner</a> about whats right for you. </p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/condiments_1050-x-590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=49A16D37D1D47704A80D6287373CC4310D789C6A"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/condiments_1050-x-590.jpg" alt="Variety of condiments"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">It's in the sauce</h3> 
              <p>Most simmer sauces, gravies and condiments are stacked with salt to enhance their flavour. A squirt of sauce, a drizzle of dressing on a salad can really start to add up. Popular products that contain loads of salt include soy sauce, tomato sauce, relish, mustard, stir-fry sauces, marinades, stock, gravy, mayonnaise and salad dressings. Anything pickled such as olives, gherkins and capers is high in salt too. <br> <br> Hint: try to make your own with fresh ingredients when you can. Start with <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/healthyliving/recipes/view-recipes/sauce-home-made-tomato" target="_new">our homemade tomato sauce</a> using fresh tomatoes  make up a batch and freeze. Its great with pasta.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/naturaldoesntmean-_1050x590.png?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=A78B6C0C5EC2517AE8C341A235535F23FD2C30E7"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/naturaldoesntmean-_1050x590.png" alt="Man on phone at supermarket with family"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Natural? Think again</h3> 
              <p>Even though a label may say natural doesnt mean food is healthy - it could contain loads of salt. Download a free app like <a href="http://www.foodswitch.com.au/" target="_new">FoodSwitch</a>, which scans barcodes and gives the nutritional value of loads of foods. If you have kids, get them to help with the shopping. They can search for healthy alternatives using your phone  its great for starting healthy habits early in their lives. The best way to ensure were eating natural foods is to eat plenty of fruit, vegetables and wholegrains.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/dont_listen_to_cravings_1050x590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=8C05657000335D7113D09B20386B3A08DDC74E5F"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/dont_listen_to_cravings_1050x590.jpg" alt="Takeaway hamburgers and chips"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Don't listen to those cravings</h3> 
              <p>Salt has a craving effect on our bodies  the more we eat, the more we want. And, for some of us, it makes us eat more too. Try to cut down slowly, so you're less likely to crave 'bad things', such as junk and fast foods! Dont be disheartened, foods might taste different from the start, but our taste buds will adjust  it just takes time. So stick with it. If you find you are craving excessively, see a doctor  it could be a sign of an underlying medical condition, such as <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/conditionsandtreatments/addisons-disease" target="_new">Addisons disease</a>.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/breakfast_1050-x-590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=112FAB530120F7154DA90E5C7CD3E1E21A5AC6F6"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/breakfast_1050-x-590.jpg" alt="Bircher muesli"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Surely not breakfast!</h3> 
              <p>Believe it or not, <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/breakfast" target="_new">breakfast</a> cereals can be high in salt, and that toast were eating could be too. When shopping, read the nutritional information and make sure to look for low sodium products. Your best bet is to choose cereals that are less likely to contain added salt such as oats or unsweetened muesli. If you have time, make your own <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/healthyliving/recipes/view-recipes/muesli-bircher" target="_new">Bircher muesli</a>  its cheaper, healthier and filling!</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/lunch_or_brunch_1050x590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=CFF42ABA9BE16B47BC859E6046A83704217F546E"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/lunch_or_brunch_1050x590.jpg" alt="Packing a homemade lunch"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Time for brunch or lunch?</h3> 
              <p>A popular lunch staple is the humble sandwich or roll filled with deli meats. Even if you make your own lunch you may not know exactly how much salt youre actually consuming. Limit your intake of deli meats that are high in salt such as salami, ham, corned beef, and chicken loaf. Go easy on those Sunday brunches too  smoked salmon, sausages, bacon and prosciutto are high in salt  just one rasher of bacon alone is a third of our maximum daily intake! Be on the lookout for brands that are lower in sodium. <br> <br> Hint: <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/lunch-boxes-healthy-ideas" target="_new">vary fillings in lunches</a>  such as tuna in spring water (it's less salty than brine), hard-boiled eggs, or patties and dips made with legumes (e.g. falafels or <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/healthyliving/recipes/view-recipes/dip-hommus" target="_new">hommus</a>.)</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/convert_sodium_1050x590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=B788A8D1A27F1DEEAB6AE4D5892B849BE4B638E5"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/convert_sodium_1050x590.jpg" alt="Healthy calculator"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Converting sodium into salt</h3> 
              <p>If youre still confused by <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/food-labels" target="_new">food labels</a> try this simple calculation to work out how much salt is in a product: <br> <br> Multiply the amount of sodium (in mg) by 2.5 <br> <br> <i>For example: 400 mg sodium in a serve of food X 2.5 = 1,000 mg (or 1 gram) of salt</i> </p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
           <li> 
            <div class="gallery-item"> 
             <div class="image" data-gallery-thumbnail="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/cramps_1050-x-590.jpg?bc=black&amp;h=56&amp;w=100&amp;hash=398656D525B60D345489795FB7D18D67CADD7966"> 
              <img src="/-/media/bhc/images/slideshow/cut-down-on-salt/cramps_1050-x-590.jpg" alt="Man with cramp on the running track"> 
             </div> 
             <div class="content"> 
              <h3 class="title">Cramps don't need salt</h3> 
              <p>Contrary to what we might believe, <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/conditionsandtreatments/muscle-cramp" target="_new">if your muscles are cramping</a> they need water not salt. Cramps are a sign that our body is dehydrated and needs replenishing. <a href="https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/health/healthyliving/Exercise-the-low-down-on-water-and-drinks" target="_new">Drink plenty of water before, during and after exercise,</a> and especially on hot days.</p> 
             </div> 
            </div> </li> 
          </ol> 
         </div>

          <h2>BMI Calculator&nbsp;</h2> 
          <p>Body Mass Index is used to estimate your total amount of fat. It is only an approximate measure of the best weight for your health.</p> 
          <p>This calculator is designed for men and women over the age of 18.</p>
